          devanagari: "हा हा विभो जलमहं न्यपिबं पुरस्ता-\nदद्यापि मज्जति मही किमहं करोमि ।\nइत्थं त्वदङ्घ्रियुगलं शरणं यतोऽस्य\nनासापुटात् समभवः शिशुकोलरूपी ॥",
          transliteration: "hā hā vibhō jalamahṁ nyapibaṁ purastā-\ndadyāpi majjati mahī kimahṁ karōmi |\nitthaṁ tvadaṅghriyugalaṁ śaraṇaṁ yatō'sya\nnāsāpuṭāt samabhavaḥ śiśukōlarūpī ||",
          translation: "'Alas, O Lord! I had drunk up the waters before, and yet the Earth sinks again — what can I do?' As Brahma thus surrendered at Your two feet, You emerged from his nostril in the form of a tiny boar-cub!",
          commentary: "Brahma's lament reveals his limitations — he had previously absorbed the cosmic waters during creation, yet is powerless now. The moment he surrenders (tvadanghriyugalam sharanam), the Lord manifests immediately from his nostril as a 'shishukola' — a baby boar, tiny and seemingly insignificant. This miraculous emergence from Brahma's breath symbolizes that the Lord pervades all creation and can manifest through any medium when devotees surrender.",
